text: Oh hi everyone you're scaring the white
people here the Internet's busiest music
nerd and it is time for a review of the
new crunk bin record Mordecai
this is the latest full-length LP from
Texas trio krugman their second album
for the dead oceans label it has now
been a few years since I first began to
hear a lot of hype bubbling around this
band with their sophomore release con
todo el mundo being a big breakout
moment for them transcending cultural
barriers in the industry and the
internet using this vintage and
psychedelic blend of funk soul disco
rock really anything they can squeeze a
groove out of in its best moments con
todo is body rocking and sounded like
something out of a 70s film soundtrack
but in its worst moments it's basically
second-rate vibe music or vaguely groovy
wallpaper with a nostalgic twist now in
comparison with their last LP Mordecai
does seem to feature better production
but the tracklist is similarly spotty
and that we're getting a combination of
songs that make me want to get out of my
chair and dance and songs that make me
want to go to sleep the only track that
really engaged me on this project was
the only song I enjoyed going into it
and that is pelota which is a super
funky Latin number with sticky group
vocal refrains nimble bassline handclaps
flavorful guitar leads to it is not just
a vibe it is a legitimately good song
that I've been finding myself going back
to again and again but everything else
on this album and I do mean everything
is just operating in in various degrees
of boredom and blandness and that would
be because in terms of what they have
presented here this band is just not
that strong or interesting of a force
instrumentally or aesthetically the
opening track first class is so tedious
and such a chore to listen to why would
you kick your record off with this song
unless you were trying to set
expectations as low as possible this
song would basically be unlistenable if
not for the super tight
humming the bass line gets stale before
two minutes of the song is even up the
guitar playing is sloppy as hell like
very messy and quietly and faintly mixed
into the song so people won't notice I
think like I get the appeal of the
twangy reverb II tone of the guitar it
certainly fits within the aesthetic of
the bass and the drums and the somewhat
old-school sound of the track but it's
not very well played and unfortunately
there are equally underwhelming songs to
follow father bird mother bird is a
moody and melodic instrumental where
once again the guitar takes the lead but
all of the fluttering repetitive
pentatonic notes all over the song just
aren't really that engaging or
interesting so are the embellishments
and improvisation zhan this track
supposed to be keeping things afloat
and engaging because they're just not
it's no john mclaughlin i'll say that
the track want to remember ironically is
an utterly forgettable reggae number
which at first does kind of grab my
attention because it is a change in
style it is a change in groove sure to
start it doesn't sound like the same
vaguely psychedelic soul PAP that is
delivered throughout the rest of this
record but then it trails off into some
of the most boring attempts I've ever
heard to capture the magic of dub reggae
the delays are just so basic and quiet
and barely even there and the subtly
psychedelic guitars don't really add
that much flavor to the song with the
track dearest Alfred the sound of the
guitars bass and drums all that is
pretty well established at this point
but is there like I don't know a benefit
to mixing and placing everything in a
way where it is so quiet and not really
leaving much of an impression mind you
it's not dreamy it's not ambient it's
not low-key to the point Road come off
super subtle or experimental and yet
it's not loud enough to demand any
attention the forefront of your mind
basically I'm just listening to somewhat
psychedelic elevator music
Ashida we have an incredibly
anti-climactic closer with this one I
mean I guess at this point if the final
track were actually good I would feel
in some way like why couldn't the rest
of the record be like this mind you
there are a few points of semi
enjoyability in the tracklist the disco
grooves and lead vocals on time are
quite nice but the song does get pretty
stale pretty fast like it could have
used a changeup or two along its run
time some bolder everything as well
there are some semi catchy vocal
refrains and curious guitar leads on the
track if there is no question the drums
are funky is always as well but once
you've heard the first two minutes of
this one you have pretty much heard
everything it has to offer outside of a
very weak instrumental pickup past the
midpoint overall I just found this
record to be really uninspired and
lifeless and I get that many people may
give it a pass for being kind of chill
and just like vibey but personally I
couldn't even get that out of it for the
most part what I felt like I was
listening to was the soundtrack to a
road trip I didn't really want to be on
I have to pee really bad and I am just
like desperate for the next gas station
because if I am stranded in this place

getting locked away into musical
